  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Tenth Month's Full Moon, as Chrysanthemums Bloom in Profusion and the Bright Moon Shines Perfect—Drinking Alone with Reflections
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The moonlight is ever wondrous in mid-autumn,
    And chrysanthemums naturally grace the Double Ninth.
    But this year the rains came for mid-autumn,
    And this year the flowers have not yet bloomed for the Double Ninth.
    Having lost both festivals to circumstance,
    My heart grows heavy with nothing but sorrow.

    But what evening is this? This night in the tenth month
    When chrysanthemums bloom and the bright moon rises together!
    I raise my cup to the moon, floating flowers upon the wine—
    How can I describe such joy in a single lifetime?

    Do you not see? Li Bai gazed upon the moon, yet lacked these flowers;
    Tao Qian beheld the chrysanthemums, yet could not claim the moon.
    Even the sages and worthies of old could not achieve both;
    How then have I, an ordinary man, fulfilled both desires?

    I ask the moon, I ask the flowers: is there another like me?
    Year after year, on this day, do not abandon me.
    I grow drunk, I sing, I drink alone—
    Enumerable chrysanthemums bloom, and the moon never sets.
  footnotes:
    - Li Bai (701-762) was a legendary Tang dynasty poet famous for his moon-gazing verses. Tao Qian (365-427) was a Jin dynasty poet renowned for his chrysanthemum poems, particularly after his retirement from court.
    - The Double Ninth Festival (重陽) traditionally celebrates chrysanthemums on the ninth day of the ninth lunar month, while mid-autumn celebrates the full moon on the fifteenth day of the eighth month. The poem laments that rain disrupted the mid-autumn celebration and the flowers had not yet bloomed for the Double Ninth.
    - The chrysanthemum and moon are both central symbols in classical Chinese and Korean poetry, representing longevity, integrity, and celestial beauty respectively.
